John Schopfer, Senior Managing Director
Certifications/Licenses: Series 50, Municipal Advisor Representative
Mr. Schopfer recently joined PRAG after serving for six years in a senior Public Finance position at TD Securities in New York City. Mr. Schopfer has 36 years of experience, including 20 years at Bear Stearns and several years at both Kidder Peabody and Salomon Brothers. He began his career as an associate bond attorney at Hawkins, Delafield & Wood.
Mr. Schopfer has a broad background, with expertise in public/private partnerships, solid waste, corporate and project tax-exempt finance and bond law. Between 1983-2003, he specialized in financing waste disposal facilities throughout the country, including projects in Florida, New Jersey, New York, Connecticut, Massachusetts and California. He has led numerous general obligation and revenue bond financings as well as transactions on more than 20 disposal projects, including waste-to-energy facilities, MRFs, waste paper recycling projects, landfills and ash mono-fills. He has worked on projects in New Jersey for Essex County and Warren County, as well as the unbuilt WTE project for the Bergen County Utilities Authority. Mr. Schopfer is familiar with the original county-by-county solid waste planning process, the involvement of the New Jersey BPU and the failure of State-mandated flow control that led to the economic difficulties for privately owned WTE projects in New Jersey.
Mr. Schopfer graduated from Drew University, magna cum laude, and from the Law School at the University of Pennsylvania.
Show moreShow less


Barry Valentinsen, Senior Counselor
Mr. Valentinsen assists the firm’s general governmental and enterprise fund clients in the structuring and marketing of their borrowing programs, and has developed cash flow models for some of the firm’s most complex financings. He also has worked on securitization financings including bonds repaid through tobacco company payments.
Prior to joining PRAG in 1997, Mr. Valentinsen worked nearly 15 years in New York State Government, where he held positions that included Assistant Secretary to the Governor, Deputy Commissioner for Administration for the State Agriculture Department and Principal Fiscal Analyst for the Assembly Ways and Means Committee.
Mr. Valentinsen received a B.A. in Communications from Temple University, an MBA in Finance and an M.A. in Communications from the University at Albany.
